## What changed

`loadEmbedder()` now forces `device: "wasm"` instead of the previous
  `webgpu`/`wasm` auto-pick. The old comment about preferring WebGPU is
  replaced with an explanation of *why* WASM is required here.

## Why this happened

EmbeddingGemma is **Gemma-architected** (not BERT-style like the old
  MiniLM). When transformers.js tries to compile its ops into a WebGPU
  compute pipeline, it fails at `getBindGroupLayout` — that's a WebGPU API
  used during pipeline creation. The error surfaced through `loadEmbedder()`
  because the embedding model loads in parallel with the Gemma chat model
  during "Load assistant", and the catch-all error handler reported
  whichever promise rejected first.

## Why WASM is fine here

- **Embedding ≠ generation.** Embedding is a single forward pass over ~512
  tokens; generation is token-by-token autoregressive. A 300M model on WASM
  handles embeddings in well under a second per query.
- **Avoids GPU contention.** Gemma 4 E2B (the chat model) needs WebGPU.
  Running the embedder on WASM keeps them on separate devices instead of
  fighting for the same GPU.
- **The prebuilt cache (next step) removes most WASM work anyway.** Once we
  ship `chatbot_embeddings.bin`, the only WASM embedding work left is one
  vector per user query — negligible.

Try loading the assistant again — it should now succeed. The embedding model
  will still download on first use (~300 MB), but once the prebuilt cache
  work is done, that 30s indexing step will be replaced by an ~18 MB binary
  download.

