Understanding the shape of the yield curve provides insight into market
  expectations for the economy and interest rates.

Key characteristics include:

Normal Yield Curve: Longer maturities pay higher yields, which makes sense
  as you should be compensated more for locking money up for a longer
  period. This shape reflects expectations for continued economic growth.
Inverted Yield Curve: Short-term yields are higher than long-term yields.
  This is unusual and has historically been one of the most reliable
  predictors of a recession.
Flat Yield Curve: Short-term and long-term rates are nearly equal. This
  often occurs during transitions between economic expansion and
  contraction, signaling uncertainty about the economic outlook.
Steep Yield Curve: There is a large difference between short-term and
  long-term yields.
In academic and professional contexts, the term "term structure"
